"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapters 11–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1chronicles-11-12.py

Ch 11: All-Israel anointing at Hebron; capture of Jerusalem; David's mighty men (gibbōrîm)
Ch 12: Warriors joining David at Ziklag and in the wilderness; tribal gathering at Hebron

Key context notes:
- "Bone and flesh" formula (11:1): ANE kinship-covenant language (Gen 29:14; 2 Sam 5:1)
- Jerusalem capture (11:4-9): Jebusite city, the Millo, the stronghold of Zion
- The Three and the Thirty (11:10-47): military honor system analogous to ANE hero traditions
- Water from Bethlehem (11:15-19): David's pouring it out as an offering — gift-reversal ritual
- Gadites like lions (12:8): conventional ANE military similes for elite troops
- Sons of Issachar (12:32): proverbial wisdom tradition; counsel-men tradition
- Hebron feast (12:38-40): covenant meal ratifying the kingship; all-Israel scope (Chronicler's theme)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>&lsquo;We are your bone and your flesh&rsquo; — the kinship formula (<em>ʿaṣmᵉḵā ûḇāśāreḵā ʾănaḥnû</em>) is the standard ANE expression for claiming full-tribal solidarity and obligation. The same formula appears when Laban accepts Jacob as family (Gen 29:14), when David&rsquo;s own men claim him (2 Sam 5:1), and when Abimelech appeals to Shechem (Judg 9:2). In tribal societies, the bone-flesh declaration activates kinship obligations — loyalty, mutual defense, and shared honor — at the political level. The elders&rsquo; use of the formula signals that the David-Israel covenant is being established on the same footing as family relationship, not merely political contract.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The elders&rsquo; speech recalls David&rsquo;s military service under Saul: &lsquo;it was you who led out and brought in Israel.&rsquo; The phrase <em>môṣîʾ wᵉmaḇîʾ</em> (lead out and bring in) is the standard idiom for battlefield command — the commander who leads troops out to battle and brings them home safely (Num 27:17; 1 Sam 18:13,16; 1 Kgs 3:7). YHWH&rsquo;s word to David (&lsquo;you shall shepherd my people Israel, and you shall be prince over my people Israel&rsquo;) fuses the warrior-shepherd imagery: the king is both military commander and pastoral shepherd, the combination that defines the Davidic ideal.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David made a covenant (<em>bᵉrît</em>) with the elders at Hebron before YHWH — the covenant is solemnized at a sacred location (Hebron, where Abraham had built an altar and where the patriarchs were buried; Gen 13:18; 23:19) and witnessed by YHWH, making it a tripartite vassal-type arrangement: king, people, and divine witness. The anointing by the elders is Samuel&rsquo;s third anointing of David (first by Samuel privately, 1 Sam 16:13; second by Judah alone after Saul&rsquo;s death, 2 Sam 2:4; now by all Israel) — the progressive public validation of the divine choice.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jerusalem (= Jebus in the pre-Israelite period) was a Jebusite city-state that had survived the Israelite conquest because it was in the no-man&rsquo;s-land between Judah and Benjamin (Josh 15:63; 18:28). The Jebusites were one of the seven Canaanite nations (Exod 3:8; Deut 7:1). The city&rsquo;s ridge location between the Kidron and Tyropoeon valleys made it a naturally defensible citadel. &lsquo;All Israel&rsquo; marching together to take Jerusalem is the Chronicler&rsquo;s emphasis — Samuel-Kings records only &lsquo;the king and his men&rsquo; (2 Sam 5:6); the Chronicler deliberately frames the conquest as a national act.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&lsquo;You shall not come in here&rsquo; — the Jebusites&rsquo; taunt (in 2 Sam 5:6-8 they add &lsquo;the blind and the lame can ward you off&rsquo;) may reflect confidence in the city&rsquo;s fortifications. The <strong>stronghold of Zion</strong> (<em>mᵉṣuḏat ṣiyyôn</em>) = the fortified ridge, subsequently called &lsquo;the city of David.&rsquo; Zion is first used here as a place name; it will become the theological designation for Jerusalem as YHWH&rsquo;s chosen city (Ps 2:6; 9:11; 48:1). The Jebusites&rsquo; taunt about the blind and lame is omitted by the Chronicler — his account focuses on the positive achievement.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&lsquo;Whoever strikes the Jebusites first shall be chief and captain&rsquo; — a military incentive system rewarding individual initiative, analogous to the Achilles-type warrior who wins honor through the first blow. Joab son of Zeruiah leads the assault and becomes army commander (<em>śar ṣāḇāʾ</em>). Joab will remain David&rsquo;s military chief throughout the reign, a figure of enormous power and moral complexity (the murderer of Abner, Amasa, and Absalom) — the Chronicler introduces him here in his legitimizing role as conquest-hero, omitting the later problematic episodes.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&lsquo;The city of David&rsquo; — the renaming of the Jebusite stronghold after its conqueror is standard ANE practice for establishing sovereignty (cf. Alexander&rsquo;s naming of cities Alexandria). More significantly, it makes Jerusalem an extension of David&rsquo;s personal identity: the city is his by conquest, by naming, and by residence. The Chronicler will connect this to the temple project — Zion/the city of David becomes the location of the ark and the site of the future temple (1 Chr 15:1; 2 Chr 3:1).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The <strong>Millo</strong> (<em>hamillôʾ</em>, from <em>māleʾ</em>, to fill) was a massive earthen terrace or fill-construction that supported the northern expansion of Jerusalem&rsquo;s ridge — archaeologically associated with the large stone structure excavated on the eastern slope of the City of David by Eilat Mazar. The Millo represents major urban engineering infrastructure; its construction/repair is attributed to David here, Solomon (1 Kgs 9:15,24), and Hezekiah (2 Chr 32:5). Joab repaired &lsquo;the rest of the city&rsquo; — the divided responsibility (David the citadel, Joab the residential area) reflects the administrative division of urban building projects.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&lsquo;YHWH of hosts was with him&rsquo; — <em>YHWH ṣᵉḇāʾôt</em> is a title that appears more than 260 times in the OT; it denotes YHWH in his role as commander of the heavenly armies and patron of Israel&rsquo;s earthly armies. The formula &lsquo;YHWH was with him&rsquo; is the Deuteronomistic evaluative phrase for divinely favored royal success (used of Joshua, Samuel, Saul initially, David consistently). David&rsquo;s &lsquo;growing greater and greater&rsquo; (<em>hālaḵ wᵉgāḏôl</em>) is the standard idiom for increasing power and reputation — the same root in Abraham&rsquo;s growing greatness (Gen 24:35).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The introduction to the <strong>gibbōrîm</strong> (mighty men/warriors) lists characterizes them as those who &lsquo;gave him strong support (<em>yithḥazzᵉqû ʿimmô</em>) in his kingdom, along with all Israel.&rsquo; The <em>gibbōr</em> (pl. <em>gibbōrîm</em>) is the warrior-hero category in Hebrew: the man of physical prowess, battlefield excellence, and social honor. David&rsquo;s <em>gibbōrîm</em> have parallels in other ANE hero traditions — Mesopotamian royal inscriptions list the king&rsquo;s elite warriors by name and deed, as do Hittite military texts. The list in vv11-47 is the longest roster of named warriors in the OT and serves the Chronicler&rsquo;s purpose of demonstrating all-Israel support for David.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Jashobeam the Hachmonite, &lsquo;chief of the thirty.&rsquo; The name &lsquo;Hachmonite&rsquo; may indicate descent from Hachmoni (1 Chr 27:32: Jehiel son of Hachmoni was with David&rsquo;s sons). The feat: killing 300 with a single spear in one encounter. The number 300 is an epic quantity — Gideon&rsquo;s band was 300 (Judg 7:6-7), and Samson killed 1,000 with a donkey&rsquo;s jawbone. These counts belong to the genre of heroic hyperbole, analogous to Egyptian royal inscriptions recording the pharaoh slaughtering thousands single-handedly.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Eleazar son of Dodo the Ahohite — one of &lsquo;the three mighty men.&rsquo; The Ahohites (descendants of Ahoah, a Benjaminite clan, 1 Chr 8:4) contribute multiple warriors to David&rsquo;s roster (cf. v29: Ilai the Ahohite). The structure of &lsquo;the three&rsquo; within &lsquo;the thirty&rsquo; reflects a hierarchical honor system: a small elite within the elite, defined by extraordinary individual feats rather than administrative rank.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The battle at Pas-dammim (= Ephes-dammim in 1 Sam 17:1, the same valley where David fought Goliath) over a field of barley. Barley was the common grain of the Levantine highlands — cheaper and more drought-resistant than wheat — and a barley field was worth defending as subsistence resource. The field detail is not incidental: the battle is over real agricultural territory, and holding it is a matter of survival as much as honor.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&lsquo;They took their stand in the middle of that field and defended it&rsquo; — military last-stands over specific terrain are a common ANE topos. The credit formula &lsquo;the LORD saved (worked a great victory) that day&rsquo; (<em>wayyōšaʿ YHWH tᵉšûʿāh gᵉḏôlāh</em>) is the standard attribution of military success to divine agency rather than human valor — the same formula used for Gideon&rsquo;s victory and other judge narratives. The Chronicler consistently attributes David&rsquo;s military success to YHWH.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Three of the thirty went down to David &lsquo;at the rock, to the cave of Adullam&rsquo; — the cave of Adullam (near Bethlehem in the Shephelah) is where David gathered his followers during his flight from Saul (1 Sam 22:1-2). The detail grounds the story in the geography of David&rsquo;s outlaw period. &lsquo;A band of Philistines was encamped in the valley of Rephaim&rsquo; — the Valley of Rephaim southwest of Jerusalem was a key Philistine staging ground for raids on the Judean highlands; it features in the Philistine campaigns of 1 Chr 14:9,13.</p>",
    "16": "<p>David was in the stronghold; the Philistines held Bethlehem. Bethlehem was David&rsquo;s hometown (1 Sam 16:1,18; 17:12,15), making its occupation by the Philistines a double provocation — strategic and personal. The Philistine garrison (<em>maṣṣāḇ</em>) at Bethlehem would have controlled the watershed route and cut off David from his home territory. The scene captures a moment of David&rsquo;s vulnerability before his consolidation of power.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David&rsquo;s longing for water from Bethlehem&rsquo;s well — the specific well (<em>bĕʾēr bêt leḥem ʾăšer baššaʿar</em>, &lsquo;the well of Bethlehem by the gate&rsquo;) was a known landmark; every city had a primary well by its gate that was a social gathering point (Gen 24:11; 1 Sam 9:11). David&rsquo;s expressed longing is not a military order — it is an inadvertent wish that his men transform into an act of devotion. In ANE royal ideology, the great king&rsquo;s slightest desire is the warrior&rsquo;s command.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The three broke through the Philistine line to get water from Bethlehem&rsquo;s well — an act of astonishing loyalty and physical courage. The act belongs to the category of martial devotion that ANE hero literature prized: the warrior who risks death not for tactical necessity but for his lord&rsquo;s honor and pleasure (cf. Achilles&rsquo; Myrmidons). The water they bring is symbolically saturated with their blood-risk.</p>",
    "19": "<p>David refused to drink the water: &lsquo;Shall I drink the blood of these men who risked their lives?&rsquo; (<em>ḥālîlāh lî... hᵉḏam hāʾănāšîm hāʾēlleh ʾešteh bᵉnapšôtām</em>). This is the logic of gift-refusal in honor culture: to drink it would be to consume the very lives of his men, since they had risked death for it. Instead, he poured it out (<em>wayyissᵉḵēm lîYHWH</em>) — a drink offering to YHWH. The gesture transforms a personal gesture of loyalty into a sacred act: water brought at the cost of soldiers&rsquo; lives is too holy for human consumption; it belongs to God alone.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Abishai, Joab&rsquo;s brother, was &lsquo;chief of the three&rsquo; — he killed 300. The Zeruiah sons (Joab and Abishai) are among David&rsquo;s most powerful warriors; Zeruiah was David&rsquo;s sister (1 Chr 2:16), making Joab and Abishai David&rsquo;s nephews. The family relationship between David and his commanders is a feature of the tribal military system: the king&rsquo;s most loyal warriors are often kinsmen. Abishai appears throughout the David narrative — defending David against Shimei (2 Sam 16:9-10), supporting Joab against Abner (2 Sam 2:24), and pursuing Sheba (2 Sam 20:6).</p>",
    "21": "<p>&lsquo;He was more honoured than the other two and became their commander, but he did not attain to the first three&rsquo; — the careful distinctions in this honor-ranking system (the Three, the Thirty, intermediate commanders) reflect the elaborate gradations of military prestige in David&rsquo;s court. In ANE royal ideology, the king&rsquo;s warriors were ranked by their battle achievements and royal favor; the rankings were public and constituted the social hierarchy of the court. The Chronicler preserves these gradations as evidence of the elaborate state apparatus David built.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Benaiah son of Jehoiada from Kabzeel — he killed two <em>ʾarîʾēl</em> of Moab (two &lsquo;lion-men&rsquo; or &lsquo;heroic warriors&rsquo; of Moab; the exact meaning of <em>ʾarîʾēl</em> is debated) and a lion in a pit on a snowy day. The snow-day lion encounter is a signature story of individual prowess; similar tales of warriors fighting wild animals in pits appear in ANE hero traditions. Benaiah will become the commander of Solomon&rsquo;s army (1 Kgs 2:35; 4:4) — the list functions also to show the institutional continuity of military leadership from David to Solomon.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Egyptian warrior of great stature (five cubits = approximately 7.5 feet), armed with a spear like a weaver&rsquo;s beam — the Goliath parallel is deliberate (1 Sam 17:7: Goliath&rsquo;s spear shaft was like a weaver&rsquo;s beam). Benaiah seized the spear from the Egyptian&rsquo;s hand and killed him with it — a weapon-reversal that is the ultimate demonstration of martial superiority in ANE heroic narrative: killing a great warrior with his own weapon negates his power entirely.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The summary formula for Benaiah&rsquo;s deeds: &lsquo;he won a name among the three mighty men.&rsquo; Reputation (<em>šēm</em>, name/fame) is the currency of the ANE warrior class; deeds are performed not only for tactical effect but for the accumulation of honor. The formula is the same as that used for David himself in 14:17: &lsquo;the fame of David went out into all lands, and YHWH brought fear of him upon all nations.&rsquo;</p>",
    "25": "<p>Benaiah was &lsquo;honoured among the thirty but did not attain to the first three.&rsquo; David placed him in charge of his bodyguard (<em>mišmaʿtô</em>, &lsquo;his guard&rsquo;) — a different role from Joab&rsquo;s field command. The personal bodyguard (<em>gibbōrîm</em> in 2 Sam 23:8 as <em>šōmᵉrê hakkēlîm</em>) was a Persian/ANE institution: the king&rsquo;s closest personal protection formed a separate corps from the field army. Benaiah&rsquo;s assignment to this role reflects trust with the king&rsquo;s person.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The roster of the thirty warriors (vv26-47) is one of the most geographically diverse documents in David&rsquo;s career — men from Bethlehem (Elhanan), Tekoa (Ira, v28), Anatoth (Abiezer, v28), Hushah (Sibbecai, v29), the Netophah region (Maharai, v30), and beyond. The geographic diversity reflects David&rsquo;s success in attracting military talent from across Judah and beyond, building a supratribal professional corps rather than relying solely on tribal levies. Asahel, Joab&rsquo;s brother, opens the list — he was killed by Abner (2 Sam 2:23).</p>",
    "27": "<p>Shammoth the Harorite (possibly = Sharar/Sacar the Hararite in the parallel, 2 Sam 23:11,33) and Helez the Pelonite — the variant names between Chronicles and Samuel reflect either textual transmission differences or the use of different archival sources. The Harorite/Hararite designation likely indicates origin in the hill country (<em>hār</em> = mountain/hill).</p>",
    "28": "<p>Ira son of Ikkesh the Tekoite — Tekoa was a town 10 miles south of Jerusalem, later the home of the prophet Amos (Amos 1:1). Abiezer the Antothite — Anathoth was the priestly city in Benjamin, later the birthplace of Jeremiah (Jer 1:1). The presence of warriors from priestly cities and prophetic hometowns indicates the military system drew from all social strata.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Sibbecai the Hushathite — a warrior known for killing a Philistine giant (1 Chr 20:4); the Hushathites were a Judahite clan. Ilai the Ahohite — the Ahohite clan (Benjamin) contributes multiple warriors. The presence of Benjaminites in David&rsquo;s personal guard reflects the integration of Saul&rsquo;s tribe into the Davidic military structure after the civil war.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Maharai the Netophathite and Heled son of Baanah the Netophathite — Netophah was a village near Bethlehem (Neh 7:26; Ezra 2:22), a Judahite settlement. The clustering of Netophathites in the warrior list reflects the dense Judahite military settlement in the area around David&rsquo;s hometown of Bethlehem.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Ithai son of Ribai from Gibeah of Benjamin — Gibeah was Saul&rsquo;s hometown (1 Sam 10:26; 11:4), making this Benjaminite&rsquo;s loyalty to David particularly notable. Benaiah the Pirathonite — Pirathon was a town in Ephraim (Judg 12:15, the home of the judge Abdon), indicating northern-tribe military participation in David&rsquo;s corps.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Hurai of the brooks of Gaash — Gaash was in the Ephraim hill country; Joshua was buried near the hill of Gaash (Josh 24:30). Abiel the Arbathite — Beth-arabah was in the Benjamin/Judah border area near the Dead Sea.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Azmaveth the Baharumite — Bahurim was a Benjaminite village near Jerusalem where Shimei cursed David (2 Sam 16:5-8). Eliahba the Shaalbonite — Shaalbim was a Danite town in the western foothills (Judg 1:35). The geographic scatter of these warriors — from Ephraim to Dan to Benjamin — demonstrates the supratribal character of David&rsquo;s professional military.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The sons of Hashem the Gizonite — Gizon is otherwise unknown; some manuscripts read &lsquo;Gunite.&rsquo; Jonathan son of Shage the Hararite — the hill-country designation recurs; the terrain of the central highlands produced the men of David&rsquo;s personal corps.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Ahiam son of Sacar the Hararite (= son of Sharar in 2 Sam 23:33 — textual variant). Eliphal son of Ur — the name Ur evokes the Chaldean city of Abraham&rsquo;s origin; whether this is a patrimonial name or geographic origin is unclear.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Hepher the Mecherathite and Ahijah the Pelonite — the Mecherathite designation is otherwise unattested; some scholars emend to &lsquo;Maacathite&rsquo; (a population near the Sea of Galilee). The Pelonite designation recurs (cf. Helez in v27), possibly meaning &lsquo;of Palon&rsquo; or being a textual corruption of &lsquo;Paltite&rsquo; (2 Sam 23:26).</p>",
    "37": "<p>Hezro the Carmelite (= Carmel in the Judean hill country, south of Hebron — not the northern Mount Carmel) and Naarai son of Ezbai (= Paarai the Arbite in 2 Sam 23:35, another textual variant). These name variations between Chronicles and Samuel point to divergent archival sources rather than errors.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Joel the brother of Nathan — possibly the prophet Nathan&rsquo;s brother, placing a royal-prophet family connection in the warrior list. Mibhar son of Hagri — the Hagrites were an Arab/Ishmaelite group east of the Jordan (1 Chr 5:10,19); a Hagrite warrior in David&rsquo;s corps shows the ethnic openness of his military recruitment.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Zelek the Ammonite — an Ammonite warrior in David&rsquo;s corps demonstrates the ethnic diversity of his professional military: Moabites, Hittites, Ammonites were included. Naharai the Berothite (= from Beeroth, a Hivite city absorbed into Benjamin, Josh 9:17), who was Joab&rsquo;s armor-bearer — the armor-bearer (<em>nōśēʾ kēlîm</em>) was the highest-ranking personal aide to a field commander.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Ira the Ithrite and Gareb the Ithrite — the Ithrites were a family within Judah&rsquo;s Caleb clan (1 Chr 2:53); their appearance here reflects the Calebite connection to David (David married Abigail, widow of Nabal the Calebite; 1 Sam 25:3,42).</p>",
    "41": "<p><strong>Uriah the Hittite</strong> — the most significant name in the entire list, for readers who know the narrative. Uriah was the loyal soldier whose wife Bathsheba David took and whose death David arranged (2 Sam 11). The Chronicler lists him here without comment — his presence in the Thirty testifies to his status as one of David&rsquo;s most distinguished warriors. Hittite identity (<em>haḥittî</em>) is not problematic in the Davidic military (see also v13: Hepher the Mecherathite); ethnic Hittite men served throughout the Levant into the Iron Age.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Adina son of Shiza the Reubenite — Reubenite warriors in David&rsquo;s corps indicate Transjordanian tribal representation. &lsquo;A commander of the Reubenites, and thirty with him&rsquo; — Adina brings his own contingent of thirty, suggesting a sub-unit of Transjordanian forces attached to the royal corps.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Hanan son of Maacah — Maacah was an Aramean kingdom north of Israel (Josh 12:5; 2 Sam 10:6-8); a man from Maacah in David&rsquo;s corps reflects the Aramean borderland connections of the Davidic empire. Joshaphat the Mithnite — Mithnite is otherwise unknown; possibly a geographic designation from the Transjordan.</p>",
    "44": "<p>Uzzia the Ashterathite — Ashtaroth was the capital of Bashan, the Transjordanian region (Deut 1:4; Josh 9:10); an Ashterathite warrior confirms Bashan as part of David&rsquo;s military recruitment zone. Shama and Jeiel sons of Hothan the Aroerite — Aroer was a Transjordanian town on the Arnon River (Deut 2:36; Josh 12:2).</p>",
    "45": "<p>Jediael son of Shimri and Joha his brother the Tizite — Jediael is also a Benjaminite name (1 Chr 7:6,10-11); the Tizite designation is unattested elsewhere. The pairing of brothers in the warrior list (Jediael and Joha; Shama and Jeiel in v44; Jasiel and Obadiah in v47) reflects the family-unit structure of tribal military service.</p>",
    "46": "<p>Eliel the Mahavite — Mahaveh is otherwise unknown. Jeribai and Joshaviah sons of Elnaam — two more paired brothers. Ithmah the Moabite — a Moabite warrior in David&rsquo;s corps; the Moabite connection runs through Ruth the Moabitess, great-grandmother of David (Ruth 4:17-22). David&rsquo;s openness to Moabite military service reflects the Ruth genealogy&rsquo;s normalizing of that relationship.</p>",
    "47": "<p>Eliel, Obed, and Jaasiel the Mesobaite — the final three warriors. Mesobaite is unattested; some read &lsquo;Zobahite&rsquo; (from Zobah, an Aramean kingdom). The warrior list ends abruptly, giving no total count for the Thirty (the actual number in the list exceeds thirty, which has puzzled commentators — possibly reflecting additions over time to an original core of thirty). The list as a whole is the Chronicler&rsquo;s tribute to the institutional depth of David&rsquo;s military kingdom.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>The Ziklag section (vv1-22) narrates warriors who joined David before his accession, during his time as a Philistine vassal. <strong>Ziklag</strong> was a town in the Negev given to David by Achish king of Gath (1 Sam 27:6); it became his base of operations for approximately 16 months during his flight from Saul. The Chronicler, who omits the narrative of David&rsquo;s Philistine vassalage entirely (1 Sam 27-29), presents these warriors as coming to David while he &lsquo;kept himself hidden from Saul&rsquo; — the emphasis is on loyalty under persecution, not on the political complexity of David&rsquo;s Philistine service.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Benjaminite warriors were &lsquo;armed with bows and could use both right and left hands to sling stones and shoot arrows.&rsquo; Ambidexterity with bow and sling was a highly prized military skill — the Benjaminite warriors of Judges 20:16 (700 who could sling stones with either hand) demonstrates the tribe&rsquo;s reputation for this specialized capability. Slingers were the ancient world&rsquo;s equivalent of artillery: accurate stone-throwers could hit a target at ranges of 200-400 meters. The mention that these were from Benjamin — Saul&rsquo;s own tribe — is theologically pointed: even Saul&rsquo;s kinsmen abandoned him for David.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Chief Ahiezer and Joash, sons of Shemaah the Gibeathite — Gibeah was Saul&rsquo;s hometown; Ahiezer and Joash are from the royal family&rsquo;s territory. Jeziel and Pelet sons of Azmaveth — Azmaveth was a village near Jerusalem (Neh 12:29; Ezra 2:24). The Gibeathite-Azmaveth pairing places these warriors in Benjamin&rsquo;s heartland, making their defection to David geographically and politically significant.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ishmaiah the Gibeonite, &lsquo;a mighty man among the thirty and leader over them&rsquo; — the Gibeonites were not Israelites but Hivites who had obtained a treaty with Israel through deception (Josh 9); they became permanent temple servants (<em>nĕtînîm</em>, cf. 1 Chr 9:2). The inclusion of a Gibeonite leader in David&rsquo;s corps demonstrates the ethnic breadth of his following. The parenthetical &lsquo;leader over them&rsquo; may mean leader of the group of Benjaminites/Gibeonites rather than of the entire Thirty.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Five warriors — Eluzai, Jerimoth, Bealiah, Shemariah, and Shephatiah — designated as Haruphite. Hareph/Haruph was a Judahite clan (1 Chr 2:51) — the presence of Judahites among the Benjaminite contingent reflects the mixed geographic origins of this section&rsquo;s warriors. The Haruphite designation may indicate a settlement in Benjamin territory.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Korahites — an elite clan within the Levites (descendants of Korah, the gatekeepers of 1 Chr 9:19). The presence of Levitical Korahites in a military list reflects the broader clan of Korah&rsquo;s Benjaminite connections rather than strictly Levitical warriors.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Joelah and Zebadiah, sons of Jeroham of Gedor — Gedor was a Judahite town in the Hebron hills; some manuscripts read &lsquo;Gedar.&rsquo; The Jeroham-of-Gedor detail may overlap with the Simeonite-Gedor settlement of 1 Chr 4:39, suggesting this section draws from territorial genealogies as well as warrior lists.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Gadite warriors from the Transjordan joined David in &lsquo;the stronghold in the wilderness&rsquo; (= the cave of Adullam or similar; 1 Sam 22:1-5). Their qualifications: &lsquo;fit for battle, armed with shield and spear; their faces were like the faces of lions, and they were as swift as gazelles on the mountains.&rsquo; These are standard ANE military similes: the lion for ferocity and the gazelle for speed appear together in military contexts in Mesopotamian and Egyptian texts. The Gadite territory east of the Jordan was exposed to raids from Moab and Ammon, producing hardened fighting men.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ezer the first, Obadiah the second, Eliab the third — the numbered roster of Gadite captains. The numbering by ordinals (first, second, third) rather than rank titles reflects a military census format, organized for administrative rather than narrative purposes. The Chronicler preserves the administrative structure of David&rsquo;s Transjordanian military enrollment.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Mishmannah the fourth, Jeremiah the fifth — continuing the Gadite enrollment. Two warriors named Jeremiah appear in the list (vv10,13), which suggests these are historical individuals whose names were preserved in the administrative record rather than a literary construction. Duplicate names within a short list are rare in literary invention but common in actual enrollment records.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Attai the sixth, Eliel the seventh — continuing the numerical sequence. The military organizational principle of twelve captains over twelve units (echoing the twelve tribes) may underlie the Gadite roster&rsquo;s structure, though the Chronicler does not make this explicit.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Johanan the eighth, Elzabad the ninth — the only warrior in the Gadite list described with additional detail is Elzabad in v12 (whose &lsquo;brothers&rsquo; Elihu and Zillethai were commanders, v20). The name Elzabad recurs in different tribal contexts (1 Chr 26:7: a gatekeeper), reflecting its use as a given name across multiple clans.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Jeremiah the tenth, Machbanai the eleventh — concluding the Gadite officer corps. The total of eleven named officers for the Gadites may reflect an incomplete source or a deliberate count; the summary (v14) notes &lsquo;these Gadites were captains of the army.&rsquo; The absence of a twelfth suggests the list may be drawn from an actual enrollment document that preserved what survived.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&lsquo;The least of them commanded a hundred men, the greatest commanded a thousand.&rsquo; The decimal organization of the Israelite military (units of ten, fifty, hundred, thousand) is the standard ANE military structure attested in Ugaritic texts (<em>rb ʿšrt</em>, commander of ten; <em>rb špšm</em>, commander of fifty) and in Israelite law (Exod 18:21,25; Deut 1:15). The Gadite officers&rsquo; minimum command of 100 indicates an elite unit — in the ancient Near East, a company of 100 was a significant formation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&lsquo;They crossed the Jordan in the first month, when it had overflowed all its banks&rsquo; — the first month (Nisan, March-April) is the flood season of the Jordan, fed by winter rains and snowmelt from Lebanon. The Jordan at flood stage was a formidable barrier (Josh 3:15 notes that it overflowed its banks at harvest time, the same season); crossing it required either rafts/boats or extraordinary determination. The Gadites did it in full flood — a feat that emphasizes their warrior quality. They then &lsquo;put to flight all those in the valleys, to the east and to the west.&rsquo;</p>",
    "16": "<p>Men of Benjamin and Judah came to David in the stronghold — the mixing of the two tribes (Saul&rsquo;s and David&rsquo;s own) is the key coalition that enabled the transition of power. The Chronicler presents this as voluntary: they &lsquo;came&rsquo; (<em>bāʾû</em>) to David, not as a result of military coercion. The geography of the movement (Benjamin men leaving Saul&rsquo;s territory, Judah men joining their own tribe&rsquo;s candidate) describes the gradual collapse of Saulide support.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David&rsquo;s speech combines suspicion and hope: if they come in peace to help him, they will be integrated into the corps; if to betray him to enemies, &lsquo;may the God of our fathers see and judge.&rsquo; The conditional oath formula appeals to the tribal deity as witness and judge of covenant-faithfulness — a standard ANE treaty formula invoking divine sanctions on either compliance or betrayal. David&rsquo;s candor about the risk of betrayal is unusual in a royal speech and reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s presentation of David as relationally authentic.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&lsquo;The Spirit came upon Amasai&rsquo; (<em>wᵉrûaḥ lāḇᵉšāh ʾet ʿămāśay</em>, &lsquo;and the Spirit clothed Amasai&rsquo;) — the clothing/donning metaphor for Spirit-possession appears also in Judges (Judg 6:34: Gideon; 1 Chr 12:18 uses the same idiom). Amasai&rsquo;s response — &lsquo;We are yours, David! We are with you, son of Jesse&rsquo; — is a Spirit-inspired declaration of fealty, the military oath of loyalty elevated into prophetic speech. The acclamation formula (&lsquo;yours, David!&rsquo; parallel to &lsquo;long live the king&rsquo; in other contexts) was the standard royal acclamation form in ANE enthronement ceremonies.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Manassite defectors to David &lsquo;when he came with the Philistines against Saul in battle&rsquo; — this refers to 1 Sam 29:1-11, where David was dismissed by the Philistine commanders as unreliable before the battle of Jezreel/Gilboa. The Chronicler alludes to this without narrating it, noting that the Manassite commanders &lsquo;helped him against a raiding party&rsquo; (v21) rather than the primary battle. This editorial handling avoids the problematic picture of David marching with Philistines against Israel.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Seven Manassite commanders who defected at Ziklag: Adnah, Jozabad, Jediael, Michael, Jozabad, Elihu, and Zilthai — all listed as &lsquo;commanders of thousands in Manasseh.&rsquo; The double listing of Jozabad (vv19-20) likely reflects the same individual; the name was common. Manasseh&rsquo;s defection is the first tribal defection from the north — the beginning of all-Israel support that culminates in the Hebron assembly (vv23-40).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Manassite commanders &lsquo;helped David against the raiding party&rsquo; — referring to the Amalekite raid on Ziklag while David was away (1 Sam 30:1-20). &lsquo;They were all men of great valour and became commanders in the army.&rsquo; The Chronicler rewards the Manassite defectors with military promotion — they joined David&rsquo;s corps at exactly the moment when their skills were most needed, and their integration into the command structure was immediate.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&lsquo;For at that time men came to David day by day to help him, until there was a great army, like the army of God&rsquo; — <em>maḥᵃneh ʾĕlōhîm</em>, &lsquo;the army of God,&rsquo; is a superlative: God&rsquo;s army = the heavenly host, the most powerful conceivable force (Gen 32:2: Jacob named the place Mahanaim because he saw the angels — <em>maḥᵃneh ʾĕlōhîm</em>). The comparison elevates David&rsquo;s growing force to cosmic proportions — not hyperbole but theological claim: YHWH&rsquo;s purposes are assembling behind David.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The formal muster at Hebron (vv23-40) — the numbers listed for each tribe represent armed warriors (<em>ḥᵃlûṣê ṣāḇāʾ</em>, &lsquo;those equipped for battle&rsquo;) who came to transfer the kingship from Saul to David. The numbers are large (the total exceeds 300,000) and have prompted modern scholarly debate about their historicity; the Chronicler&rsquo;s purpose is theological rather than statistical — the all-Israel scope of the gathering is the point, not the precise head count. ANE royal inscriptions routinely inflate military numbers for rhetorical effect.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Judah — 6,800 bearing shield and spear. The relatively small Judahite contingent compared to northern tribes reflects either (a) the fact that Judah had already been loyal to David throughout Saul&rsquo;s reign and its forces were already integrated, or (b) the Chronicler&rsquo;s rhetorical interest in showing that northern tribes voluntarily brought more men than David&rsquo;s own tribe — underscoring the all-Israel character of the kingship.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Simeon — 7,100. Simeon&rsquo;s territory was embedded within Judah (Josh 19:1; 1 Chr 4:28-33) and largely indistinguishable from Judah in the post-monarchic period. The separate enumeration of Simeon demonstrates the Chronicler&rsquo;s commitment to the twelve-tribe schema even when Simeon had been largely absorbed into Judah.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Levi — 4,600. The Levites are included in the military muster despite their non-combatant sacred function — here they contribute to the civilian logistical support and religious legitimation of the kingship transfer rather than to the fighting force. Their participation validates the transfer from a Levitical-priestly perspective.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Jehoiada the leader of the Aaronites with 3,700 — the Aaronites (the priestly descendants of Aaron) constitute the senior Levitical group. Jehoiada is Benaiah&rsquo;s father (1 Chr 11:22), connecting the priestly leadership to the military command structure. The Aaronite military participation reflects the political-religious integration of David&rsquo;s state: the priests legitimate the kingship and the king protects the priesthood.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Zadok, &lsquo;a young man mighty in valour, with twenty-two commanders from his father&rsquo;s house&rsquo; — Zadok will become the paradigmatic high priest of the Davidic-Solomonic era (1 Kgs 2:35; 4:4), founder of the Zadokite priestly line that dominates the Chronicler&rsquo;s vision of temple worship (Ezek 44:15). His introduction here as a young military commander who comes to Hebron for David&rsquo;s coronation is the Chronicler&rsquo;s deliberate anchoring of Zadokite priestly legitimacy in loyalty to the Davidic kingship from its inception.</p>",
    "29": "<p>From Benjamin — only 3,000, &lsquo;for until now most of them had remained loyal to the house of Saul.&rsquo; This candid admission of Benjaminite divided loyalty is unusual in the Chronicler&rsquo;s typically positive presentation — it reflects historical realism about the civil-war period. The small Benjaminite contingent represents those who defected; the majority of the tribe maintained Saulide loyalty. The house of Ish-bosheth (Saul&rsquo;s surviving son) had commanded significant Benjaminite support (2 Sam 2:8-9).</p>",
    "30": "<p>From Ephraim — 20,800, &lsquo;mighty men of valour, famous in their own clans.&rsquo; Ephraim was the dominant northern tribe in the pre-monarchic period (the tribe of Joshua, the tribe that hosted the tabernacle at Shiloh). Its large and distinguished contingent at Hebron represents the great northern tribal bloc&rsquo;s endorsement of the Davidic kingship — a politically crucial transfer of legitimacy.</p>",
    "31": "<p>From the half-tribe of Manasseh (western) — 18,000, &lsquo;who were listed by name to come and make David king.&rsquo; The phrase &lsquo;listed by name&rsquo; (<em>noqᵉḇû bîšēmôt</em>) suggests a formal roster was maintained — these men were individually registered and recruited rather than coming as an anonymous mass. The administrative detail points to the organized character of the Hebron assembly as a planned state-building event.</p>",
    "32": "<p>From Issachar — only 200 chiefs, but &lsquo;men who understood the times (<em>yōḏᵉʿê ḇîn lāʿittîm</em>) and knew what Israel should do; and all their kindred were under their command.&rsquo; The Issachrites&rsquo; special reputation for political discernment and counsel is proverbial — they are not counted for military mass but for wisdom. <em>Bîn lāʿittîm</em> (discerning the times) involves reading the political and covenantal moment — knowing when a dynasty has run its course and a new one is divinely appointed. The 200 bring not troops but expert counsel that the 200,000 need.</p>",
    "33": "<p>From Zebulun — 50,000, &lsquo;not of double heart.&rsquo; <em>Lōʾ lēḇāḇ wāleḇāḇ</em> (literally &lsquo;not heart and heart&rsquo;) = undivided loyalty, wholehearted commitment. The double-heart idiom appears in Ps 12:2 for those who speak with &lsquo;a double heart&rsquo; (flattery and deception). Zebulun&rsquo;s explicit commendation for undivided loyalty contrasts with Benjamin&rsquo;s divided allegiance (v29) — the northern tribes (Zebulun, Naphtali, v34) display greater enthusiasm for David than Saul&rsquo;s own Benjaminites.</p>",
    "34": "<p>From Naphtali — 1,000 commanders and 37,000 with shield and spear. The large number from Naphtali (the northernmost tribe) demonstrates that David&rsquo;s support extended to the geographic extremity of the land. The 1,000 commanders (one for every 37 soldiers) suggests an unusually officer-heavy force — either reflecting elite units or an inflated account of the command structure.</p>",
    "35": "<p>From Dan — 28,600, &lsquo;expert in war.&rsquo; Dan&rsquo;s territory in the far north (after the migration from the original Philistine-adjacent territory, Judg 18) contributed a significant and militarily experienced force. The Dan tribe&rsquo;s reputation for naval and maritime activity (Judg 5:17: &lsquo;Dan, why did he stay with ships?&rsquo;) may underlie its designation as &lsquo;expert in war&rsquo; through seafaring trade contacts.</p>",
    "36": "<p>From Asher — 40,000, &lsquo;expert in battle.&rsquo; Asher occupied the Phoenician coastal region and probably had military experience from border conflicts with the Phoenician city-states. The large number from Asher (larger than Judah&rsquo;s 6,800) is part of the Chronicler&rsquo;s point: all-Israel kingship means the northern coastal tribes are as committed as the southern heartland.</p>",
    "37": "<p>From beyond the Jordan (Transjordanian tribes: Reubenites, Gadites, and half-tribe of Manasseh east) — 120,000 &lsquo;with every kind of weapon of war.&rsquo; The Transjordanian tribes are combined in a single entry; their contribution of 120,000 is proportionally the largest single block. This underscores the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent inclusion of the Transjordanian tribes within the all-Israel theological framework — they are not a peripheral appendage but a major component of the Davidic kingdom.</p>",
    "38": "<p>&lsquo;All these men of war, who could keep rank (<em>ʿōrᵉḵê milḥāmāh</em>), came to Hebron with a perfect heart (<em>lēḇāḇ šālēm</em>) to make David king over all Israel.&rsquo; The &lsquo;perfect heart&rsquo; (wholeheartedness toward YHWH and his anointed) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s supreme evaluative term: Solomon is charged to seek God &lsquo;with a perfect heart and willing mind&rsquo; (1 Chr 28:9); the ideal of all-Israel wholehearted worship-and-kingship loyalty runs through Chronicles. &lsquo;All the rest of Israel also were of one mind to make David king&rsquo; — the unanimity formula (<em>gam kol šeʾar yiśrāʾēl lēḇ ʾeḥāḏ</em>) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s culminating claim about the Davidic kingship&rsquo;s basis: popular, universal, and wholehearted.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Three days of eating and drinking at Hebron — the covenant meal ratifying the kingship. In ANE practice, a covenant was sealed with a shared meal at which the parties ate and drank together as an act of covenant-solidarity (Gen 26:30: Isaac and Abimelech&rsquo;s covenant meal; Gen 31:46,54: Jacob and Laban&rsquo;s covenant at Mizpah). The three-day feast at Hebron is the covenant-ratification meal for the David-all-Israel kingship covenant. &lsquo;Their kinsmen had prepared food for them&rsquo; — the logistical detail indicates large-scale community organization for the event.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The provision list — bread on donkeys, camels, mules, and oxen; grain, figs, raisin cakes, wine, oil, cattle, and sheep in abundance — is the fullest description of a state feast in Chronicles. The geographic scope (&lsquo;from as far as Issachar, Zebulun, and Naphtali&rsquo;) indicates contributions from the far north of the land. The list of foodstuffs represents the produce of all ecological zones of Canaan: highland grain, lowland vines, pastoral herds, and coastal trade goods. The abundance is a sign of blessing — the covenant meal is itself a foretaste of the prosperity that the all-Israel kingship under David will bring.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1chronicles', existing)
    v11 = len(CONTEXT.get('11', {}))
    v12 = len(CONTEXT.get('12', {}))
    print(f'1Chronicles 11-12 mkt-context written ({v11} + {v12} = {v11+v12} verses).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
